>>59559357
I don't think naming a character Anon is lazy at all (that just seems needlessly dismissive in general) but I do think there's a time and a place for it to be used. I have no issue with the main character of short stories or one-shot being named Anon where you don't expect any more character development than in that self-contained work, or where you wouldn't want to "waste" characterization on a throwaway idea.

That's the way I prefer handling it while giving an actual name for my more "serious" works, anything more than a few chapters long or where the character would be a radically different personality than what Anon might suggest. I don't think HATSSSSSSSSS would have the same impact if Leo were just another Anon, but I'm also fine with relatively simple works like Happiest Place on Fur work perfectly well with it being Anon.

Which leads to my other point that in my mind, "Anon" isn't necessarily just a generic insert name as much as he's a character in of himself. You use Anon in a story and readers here already have some sort of expectation of how he would act, this is why I think Snoot Game was so successful in reaching people with its message as opposed to giving him any other identity since Anon already gives the impression of him being the "usual 4chan demographic" to resonate more with players.
